(Among good American workers these better fellow Americans are unfortunately not known as what they objectively are but as entrepreneurs, landlords, investors, asset managers, financiers that create and save jobs for working people.) 
Moreover the American working people haven’t wised up to the shrewd essence of the democratic form of political rule that is rightfully so highly esteemed by the pundits of the free press and political science. By carrying out elections the democratic state periodically mobilizes its people to decide what competing pack of its elite will wield the political levers of power that are necessarily directed against the same people. Whoever one votes for, the newly elected political administration of the capitalist state can cash in on the general consent given by the voters in their voting acts that they want to be ruled by the old or a new adminstration. The choices presented on the ballot make sure that this fine outcome of the electoral process for the political machinery is never up for choice. There is nothing that offers less freedom of choice than a democratic ballot. The 2016 presidential campaign could not demonstrate more causticly what is the bitter truth of democratic freedom: 'Wall Street’s crooked Hillary’ faces off 'the Donald’, a racist blowhard that brags about a real estate wealth he luckily himself had not to lift one brick for or let alone calculate a static of. What about first starting to rigoursly think about an economic system that produces immense wealth and unseen productive capacities while it systematically let millions of people who pay for it with their labor not pick its fruits. As I said - I was there. The strongest and most lasting impression I got (I'm sure it was universally shared out there) from the almost 6 hours (arriving at the venue to the time it was over) was this: I was one guy in a crowd of easily 5,000 other poeple, total strangers, and I felt I was among good friends through and through. I haven't witnessed a single instance of unkindness, of rudeness, of unwillingness to chat with total strangers. I've never felt anything like it in my whole life... And I thought, "Wouldn't it be great to see a movement where every Trump rally crowd (and there have been some that counted more than 15,000 ppl) would coalesce after the rally into a brand new township and become a distinct new settled community with its own local government, its own local economy, law enforcement, school district, etc.? Where all the residents would have the sense they are truly home among friends they can trust and like, and entrust their kids to?" And believe me, those would be towns diverse enough even to the most doctrinaire high priests of the Diversity Religion: the crowd I saw was NOT just white guys, it was as diverse as any crowd at any major sports event - all races, men and women in about 50/50 mix, all age brackets, all coming together united in a shared sense of values, hopes, convictions and aspirations... I hope and pray that one day a movement like this will emerge - and when it does America as we've known it will cease to exist, because the Hillary/Sanders rally crowds won't want to have anything to do with us. They will go their own - perhaps similar way - and they will have an America of their own. I just wonder how long their America would survive under their kind of government...?
